Barclays, Diageo, GDF Suez, Ryanair: Europe Equity Preview

-- B y   J e f f   S u t h e r l a n d
-- 
2011-05-03T04:01:01Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-05-02/barclays-diageo-gdf-suez-ryanair-europe-equity-preview.html
The following companies’ shares may
have unusual moves in European trading. Stock symbols are in
parentheses.  The Stoxx  Europe  600 Index rose 0.1 percent to 283.93. The
Stoxx 50 Index fell less than 0.1 percent to 2,660.49. The Euro
Stoxx 50 Index, a benchmark for nations using the euro, dropped
0.1 percent to 3,008.89.  Barclays Plc (BARC)  : Lehman Brothers Holdings Inc. is
claiming $500 million from Barclays Plc for allegedly failing to
pay all of the bonuses the U.K. bank agreed to when it bought
the defunct investment firm’s North American business. The stock
dropped 1.8 percent to 282.3 pence.  BP Plc (BP/)  : OAO Rosneft sees BP Plc as an “important
and strategic partner” in developing the Arctic offshore, Pavel
Fedorov, first vice president at  Russia ’s largest oil producer,
said during a conference call. BP’s shares retreated 0.7 percent
to 462.55 pence.  Diageo Plc (DGE)  : Juan Beckman is seeking to become
Diageo Plc’s largest shareholder as he negotiates the sale of
his controlling stake in the maker of the Jose Cuervo brand of
tequila, the Sunday Times reported, without saying where it
obtained the information. The shares rose 0.2 percent to 1,218
pence.  GDF Suez (GSZ)  SA: The operator of Europe’s largest
natural-gas distribution grid, which operates 13 hydroelectric
plants in  Brazil , said it declined to participate in the
country’s Belo Monte dam project because the venture’s risks
outweighed the potential returns. The shares advanced 0.4
percent to 27.73 euros.  GlaxoSmithKline Plc (GSK)  : Sanofi-Aventis is studying
the possible purchase of GlaxoSmithKline Plc’s obesity treatment
Alli, as well as its Valda cough sweets,  Les Echos  reported,
without saying where it got the information. The stock advanced
1.5 percent to 1,305.5 pence.  HSBC Holdings Plc (HSBA)  : Chief Executive Officer  Stuart
Gulliver  may announce plans to cut costs at the bank’s U.K.
retail unit, the Sunday Telegraph reported, without saying where
it got the information. The stock fell 0.4 percent to 655.4
pence.  Rolls-Royce Group Plc (RR/)  : Gatehouse Bank Plc, a
Shariah-compliant wholesale bank based in  London , acquired a
Rolls-Royce Group Plc manufacturing and logistics facility in
Glasgow, Scotland, for 52.7 million pounds ($88 million),
according to an e-mailed statement. The shares rose 0.2 percent
to 641.5 pence.  Royal Bank of Scotland Group Plc (RBS)  : A report by the
U.K. Financial Services Authority into the collapse of Royal
Bank of Scotland Group Plc has been held up by tensions between
the regulator, politicians and the bank’s lawyers, the Financial
Times reported. The stock gained 0.1 percent to 41.47 pence.  Royal DSM NV (DSM NA): The world’s biggest maker of
vitamins agreed to sell its 4.95 percent stake in Danisco A/S to
DuPont Co. for 222 million euros ($330 million) and expects to
record a pretax gain of 140 million euros on the transaction.
DSM gained 2.3 percent to 46.65 euros.  RSA Insurance Group Plc (RSA)  : The U.K.’s biggest
publicly traded non-life insurer began a search for Chairman
John Napier’s replacement as part of an overhaul of the
company’s board, the Sunday Telegraph reported, citing a person
with knowledge of the matter it didn’t identify. The shares
advanced 0.6 percent to 137.6 pence.  Ryanair Holdings Plc (RYA)  : Europe’s largest discount
carrier has approached the Irish government to acquire Ireland’s
25 percent stake in Aer Lingus Group Plc, the Mail on Sunday
said, without saying where it got the information. The stock
rose 0.6 percent to 3.50 euros.  Xstrata Plc (XTA)  : The mining company with operations in
19 countries wants Glencore International AG to pay at least a
third more than the current share price if it makes an offer for
the 64.5 percent of the miner that it doesn’t already own, the
Mail on Sunday reported, without saying where it obtained the
information. The shares rose less than 0.1 percent to 1,521.5
pence.  To contact the reporter on this story:
Jeff Sutherland in New York at 
